  "doc_id": "31306",
  "text": "There are both conceptual and technical challenges for identifying root causes. Firstly, symptoms of a bug may not reveal a root cause. For example, when a program fails with a \"division by zero\" exception, it does not tell where the zero comes from; a debugger may need to back track the data flow to find the source of the zero. Secondly, treatments of a bug (i.e., changes made to fix the bug) may often contain not only treatments for bugs but also non-essential changes (e.g., code reformatting, code refactoring, etc.) [CITATION_1] , new feature additions, many of which are intermingled. The treatments may add extra code which does not reveal the location of root causes. For example, \"division by zero\" exceptions can be fixed by adding an exception handler spatially far away from either the failure location or the root cause.",
  "correct_citation": {
    "[CITATION_1]": "1792074"
  },
